    <div class="module-body">

      <!-- Screen 1: Hook + runner metaphor -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">The first 5 modules covered the skeleton of an agent — this module covers the training boosters</h2>
        <p>By now you can understand most of the cookbook. But in practice, the same agent often gets stuck on three problems: <strong>reasoning too shallow / calls too expensive / skills too scattered</strong>. The three boosters in this module each tackle one of these symptoms.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-accent">
          <div class="callout-icon">🏃</div>
          <div class="callout-content">
            <strong class="callout-title">This lesson's metaphor: Three training boosters for a long-distance runner</strong>
            <p><strong>Extended Thinking = pre-race breathing exercise</strong> — those 30 seconds of deep breathing before the start, warming up the brain before running.<br><strong>Prompt Caching = muscle memory from training</strong> — running the same route 100 times, your muscles react automatically without thinking about the motion.<br><strong>Skills = the coach's training plan package</strong> — a ready-made, directly applicable SOP ("16-week marathon prep plan").<br>Each booster corresponds to a type of "speedup": deeper thinking, faster repetition, broader skills. Any agent can equip any of them.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pattern-cards stagger-children">
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-1)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-1)">🧠</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">Extended Thinking</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc"><strong>What it fixes</strong>: Complex reasoning that can't be solved in one pass.<br><strong>How to enable</strong>: Add a thinking parameter to the API call.<br><strong>Best for</strong>: Math / multi-step planning / risk analysis.<br><strong>Note</strong>: Increases output token consumption.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-3)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-3)">💾</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">Prompt Caching</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc"><strong>What it fixes</strong>: Repeated spending on long prefixes.<br><strong>How to enable</strong>: Add a cache_control parameter to the API call.<br><strong>Best for</strong>: Fixed system prompts / repeated queries on long documents / tool lists.<br><strong>Effect</strong>: From the second call onward, input token cost drops to 1/10, latency cut in half.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-4)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-4)">📦</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">Skills</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc"><strong>What it fixes</strong>: Skills too scattered, hard to reuse.<br><strong>How to enable</strong>: Package "code + prompts + resources" into a Skill.<br><strong>Best for</strong>: Generating PPT / Excel / PDF and other specialized outputs.<br><strong>Significance</strong>: Skills can be reused across projects and clients.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Screen 2: Extended Thinking with chat -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">Booster 1: Extended Thinking — giving the model an undisturbed scratchpad</h2>
        <p>Extended Thinking doesn't make the model smarter — it <strong>gives it a separate scratch space</strong> where it writes its reasoning process in a thinking block, and only then delivers the conclusion. Complex reasoning tasks benefit directly.</p>

        <div class="translation-block animate-in">
          <div class="translation-code">
            <span class="translation-label">CODE · Python</span>
<pre><code><span class="code-line">response = client.messages.<span class="code-function">create</span>(</span>
<span class="code-line">    model=<span class="code-string">"claude-sonnet-4-6"</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">    max_tokens=4000,</span>
<span class="code-line">    thinking={</span>
<span class="code-line">        <span class="code-string">"type"</span>: <span class="code-string">"enabled"</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">        <span class="code-string">"budget_tokens"</span>: 2000</span>
<span class="code-line">    },</span>
<span class="code-line">    messages=[{</span>
<span class="code-line">        <span class="code-string">"role"</span>: <span class="code-string">"user"</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">        <span class="code-string">"content"</span>: <span class="code-string">"Solve this puzzle: Three people check into a hotel..."</span></span>
<span class="code-line">    }]</span>
<span class="code-line">)</span></code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="translation-english">
            <span class="translation-label">Line-by-line explanation</span>
            <div class="translation-lines">
              <p class="tl"><strong>Lines 1-3:</strong> A standard API call — Sonnet model, max 4000 <span class="term" data-definition="The smallest unit of text that an LLM processes. An English word is typically 1-2 tokens, a Chinese character about 1-2 tokens. API billing is based on token count — so 'saving tokens' means 'saving money'.">token</span>s for the final output.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Lines 4-7 (the key switch):</strong> Enable extended thinking, and give it a <strong>"scratchpad budget"</strong> of 2000 tokens. The model writes its reasoning process into a separate thinking block, then writes the final answer.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Lines 8-11:</strong> Your actual question.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>After the call returns</strong>, <code>response.content</code> will contain <strong>two types of blocks</strong>: thinking blocks (reasoning process) and text blocks (final answer).</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Huge value for debugging agent behavior</strong> — you can see the model's "inner monologue" and immediately know where it went wrong, whether it's a poorly written prompt or biased model reasoning.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 style="margin-top: var(--space-12); font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--text-xl);">Watch the model's "inner monologue" in action</h3>
        <p>A classic example from the cookbook — the hotel bill paradox. Watch how Claude uses the thinking block to lay out its reasoning:</p>

        <div class="chat-window" id="chat-module6">
          <div class="chat-messages">
            <div class="chat-message" data-msg="0" data-sender="user" style="display:none">
              <div class="chat-avatar" style="background: var(--color-actor-2)">U</div>
              <div class="chat-bubble">
                <span class="chat-sender" style="color: var(--color-actor-2)">User</span>
                <p>Three people check into a hotel and pay $30. The manager realizes it should only be $25, and tells the bellboy to return $5. The bellboy pockets $2 and gives $1 back to each person. Now each person paid $9, totaling $27, plus the bellboy's $2 = $29. Where did the missing $1 go?</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="chat-message" data-msg="1" data-sender="thinking" style="display:none">
              <div class="chat-avatar" style="background: var(--color-text-muted)">💭</div>
              <div class="chat-bubble" style="background: var(--color-bg-warm); border: 1px dashed var(--color-text-muted);">
                <span class="chat-sender" style="color: var(--color-text-muted)">Claude · thinking (inner monologue)</span>
                <p>Let me carefully break down the accounting. $30 total paid = $25 room + $3 returned + $2 bellboy pocketed = $30 ✓. Guests actually paid = $30 − $3 returned = $27. This $27 = $25 room + $2 bellboy pocketed ✓. So "$27 + $2 = $29" is the wrong way to add — the $2 is already inside the $27, it's being added again. This is mixing two different accounting categories: "what guests paid" and "what hotel + bellboy received"...</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="chat-message" data-msg="2" data-sender="claude" style="display:none">
              <div class="chat-avatar" style="background: var(--color-actor-1)">C</div>
              <div class="chat-bubble">
                <span class="chat-sender" style="color: var(--color-actor-1)">Claude · text (official answer)</span>
                <p>This is a classic linguistic trap. The $27 paid by the guests already <strong>includes</strong> the $2 pocketed by the bellboy — the $2 should not be added again. The correct calculation: guests paid $27 = room $25 + bellboy $2. The $3 returned is on the other side of the ledger — so $30 = $27 (guests ultimately paid) + $3 (returned). There is no "missing $1".</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

