      <!-- Screen 3: Prompt Caching -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">Booster 2: Prompt Caching — one parameter saves 90% of input tokens</h2>
        <p>Prompt Caching isn't a new model — it's an API flag that <strong>caches</strong> long, unchanged prefixes (a book, a codebase, a system prompt). On the second call with the same prefix, input token cost drops to 1/10 and latency is cut in half.</p>

        <div class="translation-block animate-in">
          <div class="translation-code">
            <span class="translation-label">CODE · Python</span>
<pre><code><span class="code-line">write_response = client.messages.<span class="code-function">create</span>(</span>
<span class="code-line">    model=MODEL_NAME,</span>
<span class="code-line">    max_tokens=300,</span>
<span class="code-line">    cache_control={<span class="code-string">"type"</span>: <span class="code-string">"ephemeral"</span>},  <span class="code-comment"># &lt;-- one-line change</span></span>
<span class="code-line">    messages=[</span>
<span class="code-line">        {</span>
<span class="code-line">            <span class="code-string">"role"</span>: <span class="code-string">"user"</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">            <span class="code-string">"content"</span>: <span class="code-function">str</span>(TIMESTAMP)</span>
<span class="code-line">            + <span class="code-string">"&lt;book&gt;"</span></span>
<span class="code-line">            + book_content   <span class="code-comment"># All of "Pride and Prejudice" ~187k tokens</span></span>
<span class="code-line">            + <span class="code-string">"&lt;/book&gt;"</span></span>
<span class="code-line">            + <span class="code-string">"\n\nWhat is the title of this book? Only output the title."</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">        }</span>
<span class="code-line">    ],</span>
<span class="code-line">)</span></code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="translation-english">
            <span class="translation-label">Line-by-line explanation</span>
            <div class="translation-lines">
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 4 (the key):</strong> Just this one line! <code>cache_control={"type": "ephemeral"}</code>. It means "I allow the system to cache the cacheable portion of this input." <span class="term" data-definition="Ephemeral means 'short-lived' in English. In prompt caching, this is a cache type — stored for a few minutes to a few hours (specific rules depend on Anthropic's current policy), and reused when subsequently matched. Enough to cover multi-turn calls within a session.">ephemeral</span> indicates short-term caching.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Lines 9-11:</strong> Stuffs the entire "Pride and Prejudice" (~187k tokens) into the prompt. Without caching, every question requires re-inputting those 187k tokens — the bill would explode.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 12:</strong> The actual question — only takes up a few dozen tokens.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>First call</strong>: Cache is written, timing is similar to an uncached call (baseline).</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Second call with the same prefix</strong>: The API reads directly from cache, <strong>input token cost drops to 1/10, latency drops by more than half</strong>.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>Real production scenario</strong>: Your agent carries the same system prompt (several thousand tokens) and tool list every time? Turn on caching and save money immediately.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-icon">📉</div>
          <div class="callout-content">
            <strong class="callout-title">Feel the numbers</strong>
            <p>Suppose your agent system carries a 10,000-token system prompt, with 1 million calls per day.<br>
            <strong>Without caching</strong>: Pay full price for 10,000 input tokens each time → burns through 10 billion input tokens per day.<br>
            <strong>With caching</strong>: First write at full price, subsequent hits at 1/10 → burns about 1 billion input tokens per day. <strong>Bill drops 90% instantly</strong>. This is CTO-level vocabulary — when a product manager says "AI is too expensive," you can immediately ask "Have you enabled prompt caching?"</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

